<POST>
<POSTER> cafeaulaitinfj </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2005-09-03T11:36:00 </POSTDATE>

That *is* a hard one. I'm sure most of us have unhealthy habits that
increase the cost of our healthcare. I guess if we sock it to the
tobacco companies (and I'm not dropping that idea just yet), it would
be only fair to sock it to McDonald's, too. Even I can't quite stomach
that. (I'm wholeheartedly with the lady that sued them after being
burned by their coffee, though.)

I guess the difference between food and tobacco is that no one needs to
smoke in order to live and tobacco smoke is not beneficial to any
degree to anyone's health even when used in moderation. Even McDonald's
food provides some nutrition.

I think that the risks of certain behaviors should be weighed and
quantified. The costs of the additional healthcare should be passed on
to both the patient and to the manufacturer of the harmful product if
applicable.

It's not remotely practical, though. You'd have to extort the money
from the companies considered responsible. You'd have to be able to
determine if people were being honest about their habits. You'd have no
way to extract the money from the poor. People start a lot of bad
habits while they are young and have no thought of their future
healthcare costs, so penalizing them for their behaviors years after
the fact isn't likely to prevent anything. If they don't care about the
risks of death by cancer, they aren't going to care about how much
money it will cost to die that way.

