I suspect you are misinformed about the McDonald's coffee lawsuit. Here
is a brief summary:

In February 1992, Stella Liebeck of Albuquerque, New Mexico, was
severely burned after spilling hot McDonald's Coffee on her lap. Far
from being a frivolous award, the investigation into her case revealed
upwards of 700 similar documented cases of similar burns proving that
McDonald's knew its coffee was dangerously hot. Liebeck and her lawyers
sought a $20,000 settlement, but McDonald's refused. Instead, the court
awarded her $160,000 compensatory damages (reduced from $200,000
because they found Liebeck to be 20% at-fault) and $480,000 in punitive
damages.

She was not driving, BTW. She was a passenger in a stationary vehicle.

